-- `by <hypothesis>` matches a cited LOCAL hypothesis whose conclusion
-- mentions an ENCLOSING binder. The conclusion is matched first-order against
-- the goal after peeling the hypothesis's own ∀-binders; those peeled binders
-- become metavariables, which shifts every ambient (outer-scope) variable in
-- the conclusion up by the peel count. The matcher must undo that shift when
-- lining an ambient variable up against the goal — otherwise a perfectly good
-- citation fails with "the hint's arguments could not be inferred from the
-- goal". (Top-level lemmas never hit this: their conclusions reference only
-- constants and their own binders. It bites a hypothesis destructured from a
-- bundle — e.g. the `primeDivides` field of `IsPrimeElement(d, p)`, whose
-- conclusion mentions the surrounding `d` and `p`.)
--
-- The relation `R` is abstract, so the auto-prover cannot close the goal on
-- its own: only the cited hypothesis proves it.

module Test.citation_ambient_binder_test

import Logic.basics
import Equality.basics
import Natural.basics

-- `relation` and `p` are enclosing binders; `lemma`'s conclusion `relation(p,
-- n)` mentions both, with only `n` being its own (peeled) binder. Citing it at
-- `relation(p, m)` must infer `n := m` while matching the ambient `relation`
-- and `p` through the peel-count shift.
theorem cite_ambient_through_peel
        (relation : Natural → Natural → Proposition)
        (p m : Natural)
        (lemma : ∀ (n : Natural). relation(p, n))
        : relation(p, m) :=
  claim by lemma

-- The ambient binder appears INSIDE a deeper argument, not just at the head —
-- the shift has to be applied wherever it occurs in the conclusion.
theorem cite_ambient_nested
        (relation : Natural → Natural → Proposition)
        (base p m : Natural)
        (lemma : ∀ (n : Natural). relation(base + p, n))
        : relation(base + p, m) :=
  claim by lemma
